<!-- SECTION 3: WHAT IS GSTAT APPEAL FILING -->
<section class="content-section" id="what-section">
    <div class="content-container">
        <div class="two-column">
            <div class="column-content">
                <h2 class="section-title">What Is a Trade License in Gurugram</h2>
                <div class="content-text what-is-definition">
                    
                    
<p><strong>A trade licence is a municipal-law permit issued under Sections 330 to 336 of the Haryana Municipal Corporation Act, 1994 by the Municipal Corporation of Gurugram (MCG) or Municipal Corporation Manesar (MCM) authorising the establishment, alteration, or extension of a factory, workshop, trade premises, shop, restaurant, or other commercial establishment within the corporation jurisdiction.</strong></p>
<p>Section 330 specifically requires the Commissioner's prior permission for any factory, workshop, or trade premises proposing to use steam, electricity, water, or other mechanical power. Sections 331, 335, and 336 cover general trade licensing, conditions of grant, and the offensive trades schedule. The certificate is issued annually and must be renewed before expiry to avoid Section 332 closure orders.</p>
<p>The regulatory architecture for Gurugram runs through two corporations and the Haryana Urban Local Bodies Department. The Municipal Corporation of Gurugram (MCG) covers Sectors 1 to 57 (Old Gurgaon) and most of New Gurugram up to Sector 113; the Municipal Corporation Manesar (MCM) covers IMT Manesar, the Manesar industrial estate, and adjoining belt - notified by the <a href="https://ulbharyana.gov.in" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Haryana ULB Department</a>. Cross-portal filing is rejected. The Commissioner is the licensing authority; the Sanitary Inspector and Junior Engineer of the relevant zone conduct field inspection; appeals lie to the Deputy Commissioner and ultimately to the Haryana State Government under the Act.</p>
<p>Statutory anchors run end to end. Section 330(1) prohibits establishment, material alteration, or extension of any factory, workshop, or trade premises using mechanical power without the Commissioner's prior permission. Section 330(2) gives the Commissioner power to refuse permission where the trade premises in the proposed position would be objectionable on grounds of population density in the neighbourhood or nuisance to inhabitants. Section 331 governs general trade licensing. Section 332 attaches penalty for operating without licence - the Commissioner may direct closure and recover fees and arrears as land revenue under the Haryana Public Moneys (Recovery of Dues) Act, 1979. Section 335 governs the conditions of grant of the licence. Section 336 governs the offensive trades schedule - tanning, soap manufacture, fish curing, animal slaughtering, and similar activities attract separate conditions. Property tax provisions under Chapter XI of the same Act apply in parallel.</p>
<p>An important distinction trips up most Gurugram founders. A Trade Licence (this page) is a MUNICIPAL-law permit under the Haryana Municipal Corporation Act, 1994 - issued by MCG or MCM. The Shop and Establishment Act registration is a STATE-LABOUR-law permit under the Punjab Shops and Commercial Establishments Act, 1958 (as adopted by Haryana) - issued by the Haryana Labour Department on hrylabour.gov.in. Most Gurugram businesses need BOTH; they are distinct certificates issued by distinct authorities under distinct statutes. The Sanitary Inspector frequently asks to see both during the trade-licence visit even though the Shop Act sits outside his jurisdiction.</p>
<p>Patron's role spans the full trade-licence stack - premises pin-code mapping to MCG or MCM jurisdiction against the Haryana ULB notification (filing with the wrong corporation is the most common cause of rejection and a 21-day refile cycle), Section 330 mechanical-power assessment with separate Commissioner permission application where steam, electricity above sanction load, water, or other mechanical power is involved, document pack compilation (owner KYC, premises proof, building plan, owner NoC, Fire NoC, Pollution NoC where applicable), Section 336 offensive-trades schedule check for businesses such as tanning, food processing with effluent, or animal handling, online portal submission on the MCG portal or mcmanesar.in, Sanitary Inspector and Junior Engineer inspection coordination, slab-fee computation from floor area, location category and risk factors, portal gateway payment, certificate download with QR-coded PDF, print-ready display copy, and a 60-day pre-expiry annual renewal calendar against the Section 332 closure risk. Starting INR 4,999 (Exl GST and Govt. Charges).</p>


                </div>
                <div class="highlight-box" style="margin-top:20px;">
                    <p><strong>Key Terms for Trade License Registration:</strong></p>
                    
<div class="key-term"><strong>MCG (Municipal Corporation of Gurugram):</strong> Covers Gurugram city including Old Gurgaon (Sectors 1 to 57) and most of New Gurugram up to Sector 113.</div>
<div class="key-term"><strong>MCM (Municipal Corporation Manesar):</strong> Covers IMT Manesar, the Manesar industrial estate, and adjoining belt; jurisdiction notified by the Haryana ULB Department.</div>
<div class="key-term"><strong>Section 330(1):</strong> Prohibits establishment, material alteration, or extension of any factory, workshop, or trade premises using steam, electricity, water, or other mechanical power without the Commissioner's prior permission.</div>
<div class="key-term"><strong>Section 330(2):</strong> Commissioner's power to refuse permission on grounds of neighbourhood density or nuisance to inhabitants.</div>
<div class="key-term"><strong>Section 331:</strong> General trade licensing provisions for trade premises within the corporation jurisdiction.</div>
<div class="key-term"><strong>Section 332:</strong> Penalty provision allowing the Commissioner to order closure of unlicensed premises and recover dues as arrears of land revenue.</div>
<div class="key-term"><strong>Section 335:</strong> Conditions of grant of the trade licence.</div>
<div class="key-term"><strong>Section 336 (Offensive Trades Schedule):</strong> Tanning, soap manufacture, fish curing, animal slaughtering, and similar activities attract separate trade-licence conditions.</div>
<div class="key-term"><strong>Trade Licence:</strong> Annual permit issued by MCG or MCM authorising establishment and operation of a factory, workshop, trade premises, shop, restaurant, or commercial establishment.</div>
<div class="key-term"><strong>Sanitary Inspector:</strong> Field officer of the corporation who inspects the premises for trade-licence approval and verifies the building plan, fire NoC, and owner NoC.</div>
<div class="key-term"><strong>Junior Engineer:</strong> Field officer of the corporation who reviews the building plan and the structural aspects of the premises during the trade-licence inspection.</div>
<div class="key-term"><strong>Haryana ULB Department:</strong> Haryana Urban Local Bodies Department that notifies the MCG and MCM jurisdiction boundaries and publishes the trade-licence framework on ulbharyana.gov.in.</div>
<div class="key-term"><strong>Haryana Public Moneys (Recovery of Dues) Act, 1979:</strong> The procedural Act under which unpaid trade-licence fees and arrears are recovered as arrears of land revenue.</div>
<div class="key-term"><strong>Fire NoC:</strong> No Objection Certificate from the Fire Department - mandatory for restaurants, hotels, factories, and premises above prescribed floor area at the time of trade-licence inspection.</div>
<div class="key-term"><strong>Pollution NoC:</strong> No Objection Certificate from the Haryana State Pollution Control Board - mandatory for Red or Orange category industries.</div>
<div class="key-term"><strong>Property Tax (Chapter XI):</strong> Chapter XI of the Haryana Municipal Corporation Act, 1994 governs property-tax assessment on premises within MCG or MCM jurisdiction; runs in parallel with the trade licence but is a separate filing.</div>
<div class="key-term"><strong>Annual Renewal:</strong> The trade licence is valid for one financial year; renewal must reach the portal before expiry. Patron sets a 60-day pre-expiry alert.</div>
<div class="key-term"><strong>Trade Licence vs Shop and Establishment Act:</strong> Trade Licence = MUNICIPAL law under Haryana Municipal Corporation Act, 1994 issued by MCG/MCM. Shop Act = STATE LABOUR law under Punjab Shops Act, 1958 (as adopted by Haryana) issued by the Haryana Labour Department on hrylabour.gov.in. Most Gurugram businesses need both.</div>


                </div>
            </div>
