<section class="content-section" id="documents-section">
    <div class="content-container">
        <div class="text-content">
            <h2 class="section-title">Document Checklist for Trade License Registration</h2>
            <div class="content-text">
                
                
<h3 style="margin-top:24px;">For the Applicant</h3>
<ul class="custom-list">
  <li>PAN card and Aadhaar of the proprietor, partners, or directors.</li>
  <li>Two passport-size photographs of the applicant.</li>
  <li>Mobile number and email for portal OTP and communication.</li>
</ul>
<h3 style="margin-top:24px;">For the Premises</h3>
<ul class="custom-list">
  <li>Rent agreement or sale deed for the Gurugram or Manesar premises.</li>
  <li>Latest utility bill (electricity or property tax) not older than 60 days.</li>
  <li>Owner NoC if the premises is leased.</li>
  <li>Building plan showing the trade portion.</li>
  <li>Fire NoC (mandatory for restaurants, hotels, factories, premises above prescribed area).</li>
</ul>
<h3 style="margin-top:24px;">Entity-Specific</h3>
<ul class="custom-list">
  <li>Partnership deed (for partnership firms).</li>
  <li>Certificate of Incorporation and MoA-AoA (for companies).</li>
  <li>LLP agreement and Certificate of Incorporation (for LLPs).</li>
  <li>Authorisation letter or board resolution for the signatory.</li>
</ul>
<h3 style="margin-top:24px;">Activity-Specific</h3>
<ul class="custom-list">
  <li>Pollution Control Board NoC (for industries falling under Red or Orange category) under the Air (Prevention and Control of Pollution) Act, 1981 and Water Act, 1974.</li>
  <li>FSSAI registration or licence (for food establishments) under the FSS Act, 2006.</li>
  <li>Shop and Establishment Act certificate (often co-required by the Sanitary Inspector even though it sits outside his jurisdiction).</li>
  <li>Section 330 mechanical-power application (factories and workshops with steam, electricity above sanction load, water, or other mechanical power).</li>
  <li>Section 336 schedule check declaration (for offensive trades - tanning, soap manufacture, fish curing, animal slaughtering).</li>
</ul>


            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

<!-- SECTION 9: CHALLENGES -->
<section class="content-section" id="challenges-section">
    <div class="content-container">
        <div class="text-content">
            <h2 class="section-title">Challenges and Patron Solutions</h2>
            <div class="content-text">
                <div class="table-responsive-wrapper">
                <table>
                    <thead><tr><th>Challenge</th><th>Impact</th><th>How Patron Accounting Solves It</th></tr></thead>
                    <tbody>
                        
<tr><td>Wrong corporation - MCG application for Manesar premises</td><td>Founders routinely file on the MCG portal for a Manesar-jurisdiction premises and the application is silently rejected. Patron maps the pin code first against the Haryana ULB Department notification and only then opens the right portal.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Section 330 skipped on a workshop with mechanical power</td><td>Treating a workshop as a regular trade premises and skipping the Section 330(1) Commissioner permission triggers a Section 332 closure when the Sanitary Inspector sees a motor or electricity sanction above threshold. Patron splits the filings - Section 330 permission first, trade licence second.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Fire NoC missing during inspection</td><td>Restaurants, hotels, and factories above prescribed floor area need a Fire NoC at the time of inspection. Patron diaries the Fire NoC application 30 days before the trade-licence inspection and produces both during the visit.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Renewal missed - Section 332 closure threat</td><td>The corporation does not always send a renewal reminder. Patron diaries the 60-day pre-expiry alert and files the renewal in advance with the updated document pack and fee.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Section 336 offensive-trades schedule missed</td><td>Tanning, soap manufacture, fish curing, animal slaughtering attract separate Section 336 schedule conditions. Patron runs the offensive-trades check during pre-engagement scoping and surfaces the additional conditions before submission.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Mechanical-power addition mid-cycle without fresh Section 330 application</td><td>Adding a motor or upgrading electricity sanction above threshold mid-cycle triggers a fresh Section 330 application - it is not covered by the existing trade licence. Patron files the Section 330 amendment before the change goes live.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Activity mismatch on the application form vs ground reality</td><td>Filing the activity as 'retail shop' for a unit that is actually a small workshop with a motor triggers Section 332 enforcement once the Sanitary Inspector visits. Patron maps the actual on-ground activity to the correct application category before submission.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Trade Licence treated as Shop Act (or vice versa)</td><td>Frequent confusion - Trade Licence is MUNICIPAL law (Haryana Municipal Corporation Act 1994) issued by MCG/MCM; Shop Act is STATE LABOUR law (Punjab Shops Act 1958) issued by the Haryana Labour Department on hrylabour.gov.in. Patron files both as distinct engagements with the right authority.</td></tr>


                    </tbody>
                </table>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

