<section id="faq-section" class="content-section" style="background-color: #ffffff;">
    <div class="content-container">
        <div class="text-content">
            <div class="faq-expanded">
                <aside class="faq-expanded__aside">
                    <h2 class="faq-expanded__title">FAQs: Trade License Municipality Registration in Gurugram</h2>
                    <p class="faq-expanded__lead">Common questions about Trade License Municipality Registration for Gurugram businesses, answered by our CA and CS team.</p>
                    @include('partials.faq-enquiry-form', ['enquiryLocation' => 'Gurugram', 'enquiryService' => 'Trade License Municipality Registration in Gurugram'])
                </aside>
                <div class="faq-expanded__list">
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-1">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">What is a trade licence and who issues it?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>A Trade Licence is the mandatory municipal permit issued by the local Municipal Corporation or Urban Local Body (ULB) to any commercial premises operating within municipal limits. The issuing authority depends on the city - Municipal Corporation of Gurugram (MCD) for Gurugram, Brihanmumbai Municipal Corporation (BMC) for Mumbai, Bruhat Bengaluru Mahanagara Palike (BBMP) for Bangalore, Greater Hyderabad Municipal Corporation (GHMC) for Hyderabad, Kolkata Municipal Corporation (KMC) for Kolkata, Greater Chennai Corporation (GCC) for Chennai. The statutory basis is the relevant state Municipal Corporations Act (e.g. Gurugram Municipal Corporation Act 1957 Sections 416-417 for MCD).</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-2">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">How is trade licence different from FSSAI and Shop and Establishment Act?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>Three different licences under three different Acts and authorities: Trade Licence is the municipal premises permit issued under the state Municipal Corporation Act by the local Municipal Corporation. FSSAI is the food-safety licence issued under the central Food Safety and Standards Act 2006 by FSSAI / State Food Safety Authority - for food businesses only. Shop and Establishment Act registration is the state labour licence issued under the relevant state Act (Gurugram 1954, Maharashtra 2017 Gumasta, Karnataka 1961) by the State Labour Department - for all commercial units. A food restaurant needs all three.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-3">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">How do I apply for a trade licence in Gurugram (MCD)?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>Apply online through the MCD portal at mcdonline.nic.in. Create an account with email and mobile OTP verification, select Trade Licence application, fill the trade type (Food Stalls, Storage, Manufacturing, General), premises address, ownership or lease details, workforce, area, upload PAN, Aadhaar, premises proof, property tax receipt, NOC from owner if rented, pay the fee per MCD schedule (INR 500 to INR 50,000 by category), and submit. For inspection-required trades, the health inspector visits the premises before licence grant. Patron handles the end-to-end process.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-4">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">What are BBMP trade licence categories A, B, C?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>Under Schedule X of the Karnataka Municipal Corporations Act 1976, BBMP classifies trades into three categories: Class A - hazardous trades (chemicals, fireworks, explosives, paint manufacturing); Class B - offensive trades (tanneries, slaughterhouses, fish drying); Class C - non-hazardous industries and general trades (retail, restaurants, manufacturing without significant pollution). Fees scale by category and area, ranging from INR 500 for small Class C trades to INR 25,000+ for larger Class A trades. Inspection is mandatory for Class A and B; Class C may be granted without inspection for routine trades.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-5">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">Do freelancers and home offices need a trade licence?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>Depends on the municipal jurisdiction and the nature of operations. Freelancers operating from a rented commercial premises need a Trade Licence for that premises. Pure home-based freelancers without any customer-facing operation, signage or commercial activity from the residence may be exempt under municipal-specific rules - but this varies. In most metros (Gurugram MCD, Mumbai BMC, Bangalore BBMP), any commercial activity from a premises triggers the Trade Licence requirement. Check the specific ULB's rules; Patron diagnoses based on premises and operations.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-6">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">What is the validity of a trade licence?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>Trade Licence validity is typically 1 year, renewable annually. Most major municipalities - MCD Gurugram, BMC Mumbai, BBMP Bangalore, GHMC Hyderabad, KMC Kolkata, GCC Chennai - operate on annual validity. Some smaller municipalities issue 3-year or 5-year licences for low-risk trades. Renewal must be applied for before expiry; late renewal attracts penalty and risks premises sealing. Patron's compliance calendar tracks renewal across multiple cities and intimates clients 30 days before expiry.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-7">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">What are the fees for trade licence across cities?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>Municipal Trade Licence fees vary widely by city, trade category, area and employee count. Indicative ranges: Gurugram MCD INR 500 to INR 50,000 (depending on category - Food Stalls, Manufacturing, Storage, General); Mumbai BMC INR 250 onwards by category and area; Bangalore BBMP INR 500 to INR 25,000 per Schedule X (Class A, B, C); Hyderabad GHMC variable by category; Kolkata KMC variable. Patron's professional fee starts at INR 4,999 plus GST for a single-city, non-inspection trade and INR 9,999 for inspection trades like restaurants and manufacturing.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-8">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">What happens if I operate without a trade licence?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>Operating without a Trade Licence is a breach of the relevant municipal Act. Penalty sections vary - Section 421 of the Gurugram Municipal Corporation Act 1957 prescribes penalty for operating without licence; comparable sections exist in other state Municipal Acts. Fines typically range from INR 5,000 to INR 50,000 with continuing-offence add-ons. More serious consequences include premises sealing by municipal action, denial of property-tax mutation, denial of building plan approvals for premises modifications and reputational damage during inspections. Banks and large tenants frequently ask for the Trade Licence as part of KYC.</p></div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Quick Answers -->
            <div class="highlight-box" style="margin-top:32px;">
