<section class="content-section" style="background: var(--orange-lighter) !important; border-left: 4px solid var(--orange);">
    <div class="content-container">
        <div class="text-content">
            <h2 class="section-title">Two Binding Clocks and Section 332 Closure Risk</h2>
            <div class="content-text">
                
                Two binding clocks anchor every Gurugram trade-licence engagement. The trade licence itself is annual - the renewal must reach the MCG or MCM portal BEFORE validity expiry, or Section 332 of the Haryana Municipal Corporation Act, 1994 attaches Commissioner-led closure of the premises and recovery of fees plus interest as arrears of land revenue under the Haryana Public Moneys (Recovery of Dues) Act, 1979. The Section 330 Commissioner permission for any factory, workshop, or trade premises using steam, electricity, water, or other mechanical power must be in hand BEFORE the premises starts work - a post-facto application loses the deadline and can attract prosecution on continued contravention. Diary both clocks 60 days in advance. Beyond these, the Section 336 offensive-trades schedule attaches separate conditions for tanning, soap manufacture, fish curing, animal slaughtering, and similar activities. Section 330(2) gives the Commissioner power to refuse permission on grounds of neighbourhood density or nuisance to inhabitants. Mechanical-power addition mid-cycle triggers a fresh Section 330 application - it is not covered by the existing trade licence.

